name: Michael Phelps
summary: Michael Phelps, the most decorated Olympian, is expanding his involvement in the sports world by joining NBCUniversal's coverage of the 2024 Olympic Games in Paris. He will share his expertise as a commentator, adding to NBC's team of Olympic analysts. In related news, Phelps and fellow swimmer Allison Schmitt testified before Congress to address anti-doping issues faced by athletes. Meanwhile, Phelps made headlines for breaking his own Olympic record in the 100-meter butterfly at the USA Olympic swim trials. Despite his remarkable achievements, Phelps jokingly admitted that he has lost count of his Olympic medals. He is also set to attend the Olympic swimming trials in Indianapolis, expressing his enthusiasm for the event. In addition to his NBC role, Phelps met with lawmakers alongside Paris Hilton and Randy Travis to advocate for various causes. Together with Misty May Treanor, Phelps will contribute to NBCU's Olympics coverage in Paris, further solidifying his legacy in the world of swimming and broadcasting.

name: Neil Friske
summary: Michigan State Representative Neil Friske was arrested in Lansing, facing potential sexual assault and weapons charges. The Detroit Free Press reported that Friske could face formal charges for sexual assault and weapons possession. The Detroit News reported that police initially arrested Friske on an undisclosed charge following a report of a man with a gun. After his arrest, Friske was released from jail without formal charges, as reported by UpNorthLive.com. However, police later requested sexual assault and weapons charges, according to Michigan Advance. Friske was arrested for a felony-level offense, as confirmed by WILX. FOX 2 Detroit and 9 & 10 News reported that Friske was accused of sexual assault and gun allegations but was released without charges. The Washington Post and Bridge Michigan also covered Friske's arrest and potential charges.
